\\frametitle\{Convex functions\} % Table of contents slide, comment this block out to remove it\par
 % Throughout your presentation, if you choose to use \\section\{\} and \\subsection\{\} commands, these will automatically be printed on this slide as an overview of your presentation\par
\\begin\{block\}\{Definition\}\par
A real-valued function defined on an n-dimensional interval is said to be convex if the line segment between any two points on the graph of the function lies above or on the graph.\par
\\end\{block\}\par
\par
A single variable function f is said to be convex if:\\newline\par
\par
\\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad  $f[$\\lambda$x+(1-\\lambda)y] \\quad \\leq  \\quad $\\lambda$f(x)+(1-\\lambda)f(y)$\\newline\par
\par
\\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad\\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad \\quadfor for 0$<$$\\lambda$$<$1\\newline\par
\par
Examples: $x^\{2\}$,$x^\{3\}$ in $R^\{+\}$,$e^\{x\}$ etc.\par
