\\begin\{block\}\{Definition\}\par
A real-valued function defined on an n-dimensional interval is said to be concave if the line segment between any two points on the graph of the function lies below or on the graph.\par
\\end\{block\}\par
\par
A single variable function f is said to be concave if:\\newline\par
\par
\\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad  $f[$\\lambda$x+(1-\\lambda)y] \\quad \\geq  \\quad $\\lambda$f(x)+(1-\\lambda)f(y)$\\newline\par
\par
\\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad\\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad \\quadfor for 0$<$$\\lambda$$<$1\\newline\par
\par
Examples: $x^\{3\}$ in $R^\{-\}$,lnx etc.\par
